caption: I normally like Etto, but my last order from them was highly disappointing. I ordered the greens salad, which was delicious, but the pizza was quite bad. I got the margherita pizza and I don’t know if it was a sauce issue or a crust issue, but there as so much moisture that all of the toppings slid off the pizza because the whole thing wilted and fell apart as I picked it up. The crust is like soggy paper. Not what I expected for a $45 meal.

Super delicious pizza, great Italian treats, and usually one of my favorite spots on 14th street - but the new obligatory 20% service charge for takout (!) is ridiculous. When I placed a takeout order (my first since they opened again for takeout recently) on the phone last weekend, I was specifically requested to accept the additional 20% charge (shown as "tip" on the receipt), as they would otherwise unfortunately not be able to serve me. No other restaurant I ordered takeout from, be it in the 14th/U street area or elsewhere, specifically requested me to accept an additional 20% charge. If you serve someone for an hour or two, then this would be absolutely fine - but charging me a 20% service charge for a takeout order really makes me not going to this place in the future again.

Delicious authentic Neapolitan pizza - my top pick in DC! While there are no reservations, it's well worth the wait! From the cozy brick exposed walls to wood-burning oven and in-house mill, Etto is truly authentic and reminiscent of Naples.  The classic Margherita pizza hits the spot with a pillowy chewy crust from the fresh in-house flour and dollops of buffalo mozzarella cheese and tomato puree. While the special Eggplant pizza was fun to try, the roasted eggplant and herbs overpowered the pizza. I preferred the simple Margherita pizza - less is more!  My hubby enjoyed the tender and thinly sliced Prosciutto, shaped in a delightful rose petals!  The cocktails pack a punch! The Wintry Mix Punch with Bourbon, Vermouth, and Amaro Sfumato was quite potent, the Blood Orange was subtle and hardly masked the alcohol. I enjoyed a glass of Lambrusco.  Cozy spot for date night and small groups, be prepared to wait and grab a drink at the bar! On Valentine's Day, we waited for 45 minutes. There were no specials tailored to V-Day. The Tiramisu was sold out - next time!  The daily specials are generally the same with a couple of new dishes popping up.  Etto is a bright spot on U Street. Definitely prefer Etto to the overhyped Ghibellina the next block over.

I'm on a constant debate with an acquaintance about whether or not DC has good pizza. In my mind, I am winning in favor of a good pizza scene and can add Etto to my list of arguments. Etto serves good pizza to Washington, D.C.  It's a small, no reservation Italian restaurant in the heart of 14th Street NW with bar seating and an outdoor patio. Simple candles grace each table with the glow of the brick oven in the back baking Italian thin crust pizza.  Their menu changes daily including their pizza, meats, and cocktail selection. When I went, I ordered a sausage and green tomato pizza with a fried egg on the top. It cost $17, but it was large and filling.  If you love pizza, you MUST pop into Etto!

Etto puts together a comprehensive and creative menu of pizzas, cured meats, wines, and even a few interesting salads. It can be a bit frustrating to go through every item, so focus on the pizzas and the salamis (and a salad, if you want to be healthy). The staff is friendly, attentive, and ready to answer any questions you have. We started off with a Frisee, red endive, and grapefruit salad with gorgonzola dressing and pine nuts which left enough dressing and flavor to smear the bread in. If you’re going to pick something from the cured meats, make sure you try the fennel pollen or the hand-sliced prosciuto di parma.  We really came here to try out the pizza, though. Having a strong connection to 2 Amys, we were expecting an impressive pizza. It is different from 2 Amys, but in a refreshing way. The crust is the foundation of success and uniqueness for Etto’s pizza. Apparently, the dough is made using freshly milled flour each day on a stone mill and bakes at a higher temperature in their oak-fired pizza oven which translates to a thin, but firm crust that won’t droop when you pick up your first slice. Nice and crunchy – we loved the crust – but the ingredients weren’t overshadowed. There are some interesting combinations, so we selected two – the margherita (very good but could’ve benefitted from a bit more cheese) and the potato patata chorizo tomato (the chorizo and peppers made this pizza our winner). Each pizza is sized for one hungry individual, so order enough to encourage sharing. If you can only have one thing on the menu, go with a pizza that features some of their meats. We were full and couldn't fit any dessert in (sadly), but the assorted candies caught my eye. I'll try them next time.  The restaurant is located in the trendy and busy 14th St corridor right across from Le Diplomate. The interior is cozy, and nicely done – the food and oven are on showcase. There is an outdoor patio for when the weather permits. They open at 5 on weekdays and noon on weekends. Be advised that they don’t do reservations, so try to get there right at 5 and you can enjoy the restaurant before all the other loud patrons arrive.

Had dinner with friends.  Live in Georgetown but venture into the 14th Street corridor.  Very disappointing.  WAAAY overpriced beer and pretty overpriced pizza.  And the kicker was that one of my party was facing the area where the staff hangout and saw our server and another staffer mimicking and making fun of us.  They are obviously unaware that their competition is stronger than they can imagine.  Posto, Ghibbella, M Café and Lupa Verde are all within a couple of blocks and are much better.

Just next to the newly-hip Drafting Table restaurant, Etto is a classic Italian wine bar and pizzeria that serves deep pours of even deeper reds, lots of Peroni on tap and pizzas from classic brick oven.  The toppings are unique with great fontina cheese, fried egg, and a wide assortment of Italian cured meats.  The charcuterie boards bring endless combinations, all displayed beautifully and taste as good as they look.  the outside tables can be a bit close to pedestrian traffic, but the service outside is attentive and sharp.

Stopped by for a late and very light dinner with just two or three appetizers. Fresh porcini salad was unexpected and very interesting; eggplant with parmesan was excellent, anchovies salad - could be more complex. Bread was absolutely fantastic, and it turned out they not just bake it, they mill their own flour daily in the nice wooden flour mill right in the restaurant from wheat they order from California! Never heard of such commitment to quality. Definitely will come back to try other items on their menu (due to very late time they were out of some of them).
